--- execute: echo: false --- ::: {.cell} ::: # Sensitivity analysis: detailed results {#sec-sensitivity-detailed} This Annex provides detailed results from the sensitivity analysis described in @sec-sensitivity. Each table includes the index score and rank for each of the 38 countries included in the 2019 InCiSE Index results for each of the sensitivity tests carried out alongside the results of the 2019 index results. @tbl-sens-country shows the results of the sensitivity tests varying country coverage (@sec-sens-country): * Using a data quality assessment threshold of 0.55 to determine country inclusion; * Using a data quality assessment threshold of 0.6 to determine country inclusion; * Using a threshold of 75% of the available data to determine country inclusion; * Using only the countries included in the 2017 Pilot edition of the index. @tbl-sens-date shows the results of the sensitivity tests varying the reference date (@sec-sens-date): * Excluding the capabilities indicator; * Excluding the capabilities indicator and adjusting the weighting accordingly; * Using only data with a reference year of 2015 or later; * Using only data with a reference year of 2016 or later. @tbl-sens-weight shows the results of the sensitivity tests using alternative weighting (@sec-sens-weight): * Using a 50:50 split for the equal-share and data-quality based weighting; * Using only equal indicator weights(i.e. all indicator weights equal 1/12); * Using only indicator weights based on the data quality assessment results; * Not applying any within-indicator weights; * Calculating the index as a sum of all metrics. @tbl-sens-base shows the results of the sensitivity tests adjusting the base data (@sec-sens-base): * Ranking the metrics before imputation; * Rescaling the metrics before imputation; * Standardising the metrics before imputation. @tbl-sens-impute shows the results of the sensitivity tests using alternative imputation methods (@sec-sens-impute): * Using an ‘all-in-one’ approach for imputation of missing data; * Using the ‘midas touch’ method for imputation of missing data; * Using the ‘random forests’ method for imputation of missing data; * Replacing missing data with the mean of observed values. ::: {#tbl-sens-country .cell tbl-cap='Sensitivity tests varying country coverage'} ::: {.cell-output-display} ```{=html}
